  <entry>
    <id>tag:developer.dribbble.com,2015-02-06:/changes/2015-02-06-received-counts/</id>
    <title type="html">Received Counts for Users</title>
    <published>2015-02-06T14:45:00Z</published>
    <updated>2015-02-06T14:45:00Z</updated>
    <link rel="alternate" href="http://developer.dribbble.com/changes/2015-02-06-received-counts/">
    <content type="html">
&lt;p&gt;User and team resources now include &lt;code&gt;comments_received_count&lt;/code&gt;,
&lt;code&gt;likes_received_count&lt;/code&gt;, and &lt;code&gt;rebounds_received_count&lt;/code&gt; attributes.&lt;/p&gt;
</content>
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <id>tag:developer.dribbble.com,2014-11-11:/changes/2014-11-11-team-members/</id>
    <title type="html">Team Members</title>
    <published>2014-11-11T08:30:00Z</published>
    <updated>2014-11-11T08:30:00Z</updated>
    <link rel="alternate" href="http://developer.dribbble.com/changes/2014-11-11-team-members/">
    <content type="html">
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;a href="/v1/teams/members/"&gt;team members endpoint&lt;/a&gt; allows you to retrieve the
members on a team. As a result &lt;code&gt;members_count&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;members_url&lt;/code&gt; attributes are
present on a team resource.&lt;/p&gt;
</content>
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <id>tag:developer.dribbble.com,2014-10-29:/changes/2014-10-29-bucket-project-team-counts/</id>
    <title type="html">Bucket, Project, and Team Counts</title>
    <published>2014-10-29T14:30:00Z</published>
    <updated>2014-10-29T14:30:00Z</updated>
    <link rel="alternate" href="http://developer.dribbble.com/changes/2014-10-29-bucket-project-team-counts/">
    <content type="html">
&lt;p&gt;User and team resources now include &lt;code&gt;buckets_count&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;projects_count&lt;/code&gt;
attributes. And user resources include a &lt;code&gt;teams_count&lt;/code&gt; attribute.&lt;/p&gt;
</content>
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <id>tag:developer.dribbble.com,2014-10-23:/changes/2014-10-24-team-shots/</id>
    <title type="html">Team Shots</title>
    <published>2014-10-24T02:30:00Z</published>
    <updated>2014-10-24T02:30:00Z</updated>
    <link rel="alternate" href="http://developer.dribbble.com/changes/2014-10-24-team-shots/">
    <content type="html">
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;a href="/v1/teams/shots/"&gt;team shots endpoint&lt;/a&gt; allows you to retrieve all the shots
by the team and team members. As a result a &lt;code&gt;team_shots_url&lt;/code&gt; attribute is present on a team resource.&lt;/p&gt;
</content>
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <id>tag:developer.dribbble.com,2014-09-26:/changes/2014-09-26-attachment-content-type/</id>
    <title type="html">Attachment Content Type</title>
    <published>2014-09-26T12:30:00Z</published>
    <updated>2014-09-26T12:30:00Z</updated>
    <link rel="alternate" href="http://developer.dribbble.com/changes/2014-09-26-attachment-content-type/">
    <content type="html">
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="/v1/shots/attachments/"&gt;Attachments&lt;/a&gt; now include a &lt;code&gt;content_type&lt;/code&gt; attribute, so
there’s no need to parse the extension of the &lt;code&gt;url&lt;/code&gt; or perform a HEAD request to
determine it. If you’re showing attachment previews it should be much easier to
do so now.&lt;/p&gt;
</content>
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <id>tag:developer.dribbble.com,2014-08-21:/changes/2014-08-21-buckets/</id>
    <title type="html">Bucket Endpoints</title>
    <published>2014-08-21T09:15:00Z</published>
    <updated>2014-08-21T09:15:00Z</updated>
    <link rel="alternate" href="http://developer.dribbble.com/changes/2014-08-21-buckets/">
    <content type="html">
&lt;p&gt;Access to and manipulation of buckets, an often requested feature, are now
available. You can retrieve and manipulate &lt;a href="/v1/buckets/"&gt;individual buckets&lt;/a&gt;
and &lt;a href="/v1/buckets/shots/"&gt;shots in buckets&lt;/a&gt;. As well as retrieve buckets &lt;a href="/v1/shots/buckets/"&gt;for a
shot&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href="/v1/users/buckets/"&gt;for a user&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
</content>
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <id>tag:developer.dribbble.com,2014-07-28:/changes/2014-07-28-follow-and-like-payloads/</id>
    <title type="html">Following and Like Payloads</title>
    <published>2014-07-28T12:00:00Z</published>
    <updated>2014-07-28T12:00:00Z</updated>
    <link rel="alternate" href="http://developer.dribbble.com/changes/2014-07-28-follow-and-like-payloads/">
    <content type="html">
&lt;p&gt;The followers and following endpoints no longer simply return a user. It now
returns &lt;code&gt;id&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;created_at&lt;/code&gt; attributes with the user nested in it. Depending
on the endpoint the user will be under the &lt;code&gt;followee&lt;/code&gt; or &lt;code&gt;follower&lt;/code&gt; attribute.
See the &lt;a href="/v1/users/followers/"&gt;followers documentation&lt;/a&gt; for updated examples.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The like endpoints were also previously changed to include &lt;code&gt;id&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;created_at&lt;/code&gt;
attributes, with the &lt;a href="/v1/shots/likes/#list-the-likes-for-a-shot"&gt;liking user&lt;/a&gt;
or &lt;a href="/v1/users/likes/#list-shot-likes-for-a-user"&gt;liked shot&lt;/a&gt; nested.&lt;/p&gt;
</content>
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <id>tag:developer.dribbble.com,2014-06-19:/changes/2014-06-19-comment-mentions/</id>
    <title type="html">Comment Mentions</title>
    <published>2014-06-19T12:30:00Z</published>
    <updated>2014-06-19T12:30:00Z</updated>
    <link rel="alternate" href="http://developer.dribbble.com/changes/2014-06-19-comment-mentions/">
    <content type="html">
&lt;p&gt;Username mentions are now supported in comments. Nothing has changed with &lt;a href="/v1/shots/comments/#create-a-comment"&gt;the
comment creation&lt;/a&gt; endpoint though. Any
uses of &lt;code&gt;@username&lt;/code&gt; in a comment will now automatically be parsed and linked, if
the username is valid of course.&lt;/p&gt;
</content>
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <id>tag:developer.dribbble.com,2014-06-19:/changes/2014-06-19-attachments/</id>
    <title type="html">Introducing the Attachments API</title>
    <published>2014-06-19T12:00:00Z</published>
    <updated>2014-06-19T12:00:00Z</updated>
    <link rel="alternate" href="http://developer.dribbble.com/changes/2014-06-19-attachments/">
    <content type="html">
&lt;p&gt;We’ve added new endpoints for attachments. Listing attachments or retrieving a
single attachment are available for any scope. Creating or deleting attachments
requires the &lt;code&gt;upload&lt;/code&gt; &lt;a href="/v1/oauth/#scopes"&gt;scope&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="/v1/shots/attachments/#create-an-attachment"&gt;Creating an attachment&lt;/a&gt; is also
our first asynchronous endpoint, due to the processing required. Creating shots
will behave similarly when added.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="/v1/shots/attachments"&gt;Read the full documentation&lt;/a&gt; to get started.&lt;/p&gt;
</content>
  </entry>
